Evaluation of NLP Capabilities and Applications¶

Part B: NLP for Data Analysis Markdown Report¶

Overview¶

This markdown uses data collected from the Vaccine Information Resource Assistance (VIRA), release by IBM research. There are two datasets which differ slightly in terms of their use. Both datasets will be used in order to identify any insights or important attributes from the chat bot (VIRA) regarding COVID-19 vaccine hesitancy and people's overall trust of the vaccine.

Before exploring and analysing the datasets, it's important to establish questions based on potential discoveries, which can assist in understanding the general climate towards the COVID-19 vaccination. The questions below have been developed based on the current understanding of the datasets and will hopefully be answered at the end of this analysis.

  1. Is there an overall positive reaction to the COVID-19 vaccine?
  2. Are people mostly hesitant to get the vaccine because of the side effects?
  3. Are there many people who believe COVID-19 isn't real, and is this fuelling their distrust in the vaccine?
  4. Are people concerned if they have pre-existing conditions?

As these datasets were released for potential modelling purposes, the decision to merge the training, validation and test datasets was made due to the imbalance in distribution of features, as well as more data used in this analysis, the better results. A short summary of each dataset is provided below.

Covid-19 Vaccine Intent Expressions Dataset

This dataset contains varying expressions for common questions about the Covid-19 Vaccine. Each expression has been matched to a common question, resulting in 181 common questions. The data dictionary below shows the name and a description of each column in the dataset.

Data Dictionary- Intent Expressions Dataset

Column Description
sentence the expression written by an annotatior, or taken from VIRADialogs (chat bot)
label the common question for which the expression was written
label_idx the running class index associated with this label, between 0 and 181

Covid-19 Vaccine Trust Annotations Dataset

This dataset contains the VIRADialogs, as used in the Intent Expressions Dataset, however this time they have been annotated and matched with a trust level. The data dictionary below displays the columns and a description of the contents of the Trust Annotations dataset.

Data Dictionary- Trust Annotations Dataset

Column Description
text the user input VIRADialogs (chat bot)
label the trust label:0 - low institutional trust, 1 - low agent trust, 2 - neutral, 3 - high trust

Lastly, citations for these datasets are included here:

  1. VIRATrustData: A Trust-Annotated Corpus of Human-Chatbot Conversations About COVID-19 Vaccines Roni Friedman, João Sedoc, Shai Gretz, Assaf Toledo, Rose Weeks, Naor Bar-Zeev, Yoav Katz, Noam Slonim arXiv, 2022
  2. Benchmark Data and Evaluation Framework for Intent Discovery Around COVID-19 Vaccine Hesitancy Shai Gretz, Assaf Toledo, Roni Friedman, Dan Lahav, Rose Weeks, Naor Bar-Zeev, João Sedoc, Pooja Sangha, Yoav Katz, Noam Slonim arXiv, 2022

Stage 3: Text Pre-Processing¶

This stage focuses mainly on the what makes up each sentence/question in each dataset. It's an incredibly important process as it's necessary for further anlaysis and potential modelling. The following processes will be performed on both Intent and Trust datasets:

  1. Word Count and Visuals
  2. Character Count
  3. Removal of punctuation, special characters and white space and conversion to lowercase
  4. Removal of stopwords
  5. Lemmatization
  6. Tokenization

Each process will be numbered according to the list above. For processes 3-6, the function will be defined in the code and added to for each process, resulting in one application to the dataset at the end. These definitions also mean its a simple task to apply these processes to both datasets without having to change a lot of code.

1. Word Count

By finding the word count of each sentence/question in the datasets, it allows both humans and machines to identify patterns in this type and topic of data. It provides an expected value and can be used in modelling when trying to match a sentence to a label identification number or a trust score.

The word count for the Intent data presents the following insights:

  1. Even after making each group of label_idx smaller, there is a very similar average word count for each group.
  2. The minimum average word count of 10.96 falls within the label_idx group of values between 21 and 30.
  3. The maximum average word count of 11.78 falls within the label_idx group of values between 81 and 90.
  4. In each histogram, majority of sentences have on average 9-11 words.
  5. The most amount of words is around 35 and occurs in the 46-90 group, which is where the maximum average word count also falls.

The histogram in Figure 5. provides a visual of this by plotting the word count (x-axis) and the frequency (y-axis). Each histogram presents 45 label_idx values.

The word count for the Trust data presents the following insights:

  1. Sentences/Questions with a high trust score (3) had the highest average word count of 9.7.
  2. Those whose sentences/questions were scored as neutral (2) had the lowest average word count of 6.8.
  3. Both low trust scores (0 and 1) had very similar average word counts, 8.7 and 8.6 respectively.
  4. The high trust histogram shows the maximum word count of around 40 words per sentence/question.
  5. The low agent trust score had the sentences with the least amount of words overall.

The histogram in Figure 6. provides a visual of this by plotting the word count (x-axis) and the frequency (y-axis), just like the Intent data visual. However, as there are only four trust scores, each score has been plotted on a separate histogram.

3. Removal of Punctuation, Special Characters and Whitespace and Conversion to Lowercase

Removing punctuation and special characters mainly assists with the machine learning stage of NLP, however as they also don't add anything to the datasets, we're going to remove them anyway. It will also assist with creating word clouds and histograms later in this analysis as if a comma is one of the most frequent characters, it will be plotted/graphed over words with meaning. By converting all words to lowercase, this removes any bias a capital letter might hold. By making every word appear equal visually, the importance of a word then depends on its frequency of occurrence. As white space is considered a character and can be counted, it is important to remove all white spaces in front or behind words. Just like in the process above, any white space will be counted and could mean a word is not regognised as being the same due to a trailing white space.

In [ ]:
# Convert to lowercase, strip and remove punctuations and special characters.
def preprocess(text):
    text = text.lower()
    text=text.strip()
    text=re.compile('<.*?>').sub('', text)
    text = re.compile('[%s]' % re.escape(string.punctuation)).sub(' ', text)
    text = re.sub('\s+', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\[[0-9]*\]',' ',text)
    text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', str(text).lower().strip())
    text = re.sub(r'\d',' ',text)
    text = re.sub(r'\s+',' ',text)
    return text

4. Removal of Stopwords

A stopword is a word that makes a sentence grammatically correct, but holds no value in terms of its meaning in any context. Examples of stopwords include, "a", "the" and "is". By removing these words, humans and machines are still able to know what the topic, context and general meaning behind a sentence is, only it isn't filled with unnecessary parts.

In [ ]:
# Stopword removal
def stopword(string):
    a= [i for i in string.split() if i not in stopwords.words('english')]
    return ' '.join(a)

5. Lemmatization

Is there a difference in meaning in the words "like" and "liking"? They both mean something positive and are generally used to describe how we're feeling about someone or something. Lemmatizing removes the "ing" and takes the word back to its root, "like". This allows for all words of the same lemma to be counted together. In this context, without lemmatization, words such as "vaccine" and "vaccines" would be considered as two different words.

In [ ]:
# Lemmatization
# Initialize the lemmatizer
wl = WordNetLemmatizer()

# This is a helper function to map NTLK position tags
def get_wordnet_pos(tag):
    if tag.startswith('J'):
        return wordnet.ADJ
    elif tag.startswith('V'):
        return wordnet.VERB
    elif tag.startswith('N'):
        return wordnet.NOUN
    elif tag.startswith('R'):
        return wordnet.ADV
    else:
        return wordnet.NOUN

6. Tokenization

Tokenizing a sentence splits it up into smaller parts so that it's easier to understand. For example, an entire paragraph can be tokenized into sentences, and then each sentence can be further tokenized into words. As we only have sentences in both datasets, we will use the word tokenize process to split the sentences into words. This is a very useful tool for creating visualizations and plots of word frequencies, as well as sentiment analysis.

In [ ]:
# Tokenize the sentence
def lemmatizer(string):
    word_pos_tags = nltk.pos_tag(word_tokenize(string)) # Get position tags
    a=[wl.lemmatize(tag[0], get_wordnet_pos(tag[1])) for idx, tag in enumerate(word_pos_tags)] # Map the position tag and lemmatize the word/token
    return " ".join(a)

Now we will apply steps 3-6 to each dataset in preparation for visualizations and further analysis.

In [ ]:
def finalpreprocess(string):
    return lemmatizer(stopword(preprocess(string)))

Stage 5: Sentiment Analysis¶

In this stage, we will attempt to identify the sentiment behind the questions asked. The VADER (Valence Aware Dictionary and Sentiment Reasoner) method has been used below, which gives each question a rating between -1 (negative) and 1 (positive). These scores will be graphed in order to visualise the amount of negative vs positive questions.

We will begin with the Intent dataset. Descriptions of the process will be provided throughout the intent code as the same process will be repeated for the trust dataset. The overall insights can be read below.

Intent Data Insights

  1. The most common sentiment was neutral, followed by positive, then negative.
  2. The highest positive sentiment sentence had a lot of words, even after the cleaning and pre-processing. This could be linked to the visuals in Stage 3.
  3. A lot of the sentences revolved around the word "vaccine". This was evident in sampling the data.

Trust Data Insights

  1. The most common sentiment was neutral, followed by positive, then closely by negative.
  2. The lowest negative sentiment had a lot of words, opposite to the results in the intent dataset.
  3. The sentences in this dataset appeared more direct and opinionated compared to that of the intent sentences.

Sentiment Analysis- Intent Dataset

Step 1: A new dataframe is created purely for this analysis for visualizations purposes, and ease to read the new column additions. A preview of the new dataframe can be seen below, with only one column clean_text. This is also why the text pre-processing was performed in Stage 3 as it allows for quick use in the analysis.

Step 2: Here we import VADAR lexicon, which is part of nltk package. We begin by created the object that will determine the polarity of the text. Polarity refers to the overall sentiment of the text, whether it be negative, neutral or positive. The values between -1 and 1 are then combined to give an overall compound score, which can be seen in the sample of the dataframe below under the new column polarity.

In [ ]:

Step 6: To gain a general understanding of the data spectrum, it is useful to compare the highest positive sentiment sentence and the lowest negative sentiment sentence, mainly to confirm the object performed well.

The sentence with the highest positive sentiment is "vaccination one effective public health intervention world save life promot good health clean water consider basic human right performs well despite uptake vaccine reduce country think partly cause mishuided concern vaccine safety". Even though there are no stop words, we can gain a good understanding of what this person was saying. It can be interpreted as: The first vaccination was effective and the intervention of public health around the world has saved lives, promited good health. Just as clean water is considered a basic human right. The vaccine performs well despite the reduced numbers of the uptake vaccine, partly caused by misguided concern of vaccine safety.

The sentence with the lowest negative sentiment is "die continue die serious case people die every hour". As there's no mention of vaccine in this, it can only be assumed the original sentence was something like: People die and will continue to do. The more serious the case, the more people die every hour".

The two code chunks below identify the highest positive sentiment sentence and the lowest negative sentiment sentence.

Beginning the the highest positive sentence, "ok fair want best chance prevent infection order protect others vaccine best". This could be interpreted a few ways, but due to the order of the words it seems like this sentence would be: "I think it's ok and fair. I want the best chance in preventing infection and in order to protect others, which vaccine is best?"

The lowest negative sentence is, "huge amount adverse affect range illness death feel incredibly irresponsible issue dangerous vaccine general population". I believe it's pretty clear what the original sentence was, and it could be something like: "There are a huge amount of adverse affects, which range from illness to death. I feel it's incredibly irresponsible to issue such a dangerous vaccine to the general population".

Final Words¶

Now that the exploration, analysis, visualizations and interpretations have been completed on both intent and trust datasets, it's time to revisit the questions listed in the overview:

1. Is there an overall positive reaction to the COVID-19 vaccine?

No. Neither dataset presented a strong positive reaction to the COVID-19 vaccine. Both datasets showed a strong neutral sentiment, with both datasets only having slightly more positive sentiments than negative.

2. Are people mostly hesitant to get the vaccine because of the side effects?

Yes. The words "side" and "effects" appeared a lot in the word cloud and in the top 10 words for both datasets, meaning there were a lot of questions regarding the side effects of the vaccine. Even though the lowest negative sentiment sentence didn't specifically mention side effects, it did say huge range affects ranging from illness to death, implying that the vaccine caused a large range of effects.

3. Are there many people who believe COVID-19 isn't real, and is this fuelling their distrust in the vaccine?

Lack of belief didn't come up at all throughout this process, so the answer is believed to be, no.

4. Are people concerned if they have pre-existing conditions?

Yes, they are. But not as concerned as they are about side effects and which brand of vaccine to get.

When comparing the trust dataset sentiment analysis results to the data exploration in Stage 2, it is expected that there are by far more neutral sentences/questions than positive or negative due to the highest frequency belonging to trust score 2 (neutral).

Overall, these results and insights show the public was very hesitant in getting vaccinated for COVID-19 and required more education on the topic.
